pr.body:
This PR is for implementing a `utcTime()` function that does not just use time(0) to return the current UTC timestamp. The reasoning behind this is that according to the [documentation](http://www.cplusplus.com/reference/ctime/time/)
> The value returned generally represents the number of seconds since 00:00 hours, Jan 1, 1970 UTC (i.e., the current unix timestamp). Although libraries may use a different representation of time: Portable programs should not use the value returned by this function directly, but always rely on calls to other elements of the standard library to translate them to portable types (such as localtime, gmtime or difftime).
the `time(0)` function is not guaranteed to return a UTC timestamp, even though in most implementations, as we have seen, it will. Only way to do that seems to be to combine it with gmtime() as we do in this PR.
pr.title: Fix utcTime() function

pr.body:
This pull request is for RPC support, WebThree, and libdevnet, an experimental library which supports full-duplex, asynchronous, and synchronous protocols. Third is also implemented but not usable in it's current form. It's expected to support exposing shared interfaces (e.g., RPC), encryption, framing (QoS, bandwidth optimization), and channels. Together with streaming and asynchronous support, this also means "push" is available for otherwise-synchronous protocols. The service listener (Endpoint), connections, and protocols are decoupled from each other, although Service is coupled to a protocol (via template parameters).
Notably, a 'protocol state' can out-live it's connection, services can be used without an endpoint, protocols can be used without an endpoint or service, and connections can be used on their own.
This introduces a "Protocol" class which can implement any of: interpretation, encapsulation, protocol state, and connection state. And, where a Service is used, the service may perform these duties instead.
This enables a developer to build and adapt layered protocols independent of the underlying RLPX protocol. Ideally, encryption and framing can be added to RLPX without downstream changes and downstream application protocols are guaranteed not to introduce interference.
pr.title: Code review PR: RPC, libdevnet, RLPX

pr.body: This is an attempt at prohibiting non-guarded access to a shared object. The pros are, in my view: 1. you do not need two members (`x_...` and `m_...`) for the simple use-case 2. it is harder to access the object in a non-locked state The cons are: 1. the dereference and pointer semantics are a bit strange at first 2. it is less visible what actually happens and you need to know the lifetime of temporaries 2. a unique_ptr is allocated for each lock, though that might be avoidable
pr.title: Automatic guards.
